<F P=106> ["Edict of the President of the Republic of Tatarstan on </F>
Appointing N.G. Aminov Plenipotentiary of the Republic of 
Tatarstan in the Russian Federation"] 
  [Text] In accordance with Article 111 of the Constitution 
of the Republic of Tatarstan and for the purposes of 
implementing Article 8 of the Treaty of the Russian Federation 
and the Republic of Tatarstan "On the Limitations of Subjects 
for the Conduct and Mutual Delegation of Powers Between Organs 
of State Authority of the Russian Federation and Organs of State 
Authority of the Republic of Tatarstan," and following the 
directions of the Statute "On the Plenipotentiary of the 
Republic of Tatarstan in the Russian Federation," which was 
confirmed by Edict of the President of Tatarstan No. 384 of 13 
June 1994, I resolve: 
  To appoint Nail Galeyevich Aminov plenipotentiary of the 
Republic of Tatarstan in the Russian Federation. 
  [Signed]President of the Republic of Tatarstan M. 
Shaymiyev. 
  Kazan 
  Kremlin 
  13 June 1994 
<H5>  * * * * </H5>
<H5>  Nail Galeyevich Aminov was born in 1945. He is a native of </H5>
Kazan. He graduated from the Kazan Chemistry and Technology 
Institute and the Academy of Social Sciences. He is an economic 
sciences candidate. 
  He began his work activity as an electrician at the Kazan 
fur 
combine. He worked in Kazan from 1964 to 1968 at the 
agricultural institute and at the medical instruments plant. 
After completing the institute, he was assigned to the city of 
Sterlitamak in the Bashkir ASSR [Autonomous Soviet Socialist 
Republic], where he worked at the Avangard plant. Afterwards, he 
worked in republican organs of the Bashkir ASSR--as the chief of 
a department of the Council of Ministers and deputy minister and 
minister of housing and municipal services of the republic. 
  In 1990, N.G. Aminov was elected deputy of the Supreme 
Soviet 
of the Russian Federation; he worked on the staff of the Supreme 
Soviet as the chairman of a subcommittee, the deputy chairman of 
a committee, and the manager of a department. In 1993, he was 
appointed deputy chairman of the Goskomfederatsiya [State 
Federation Committee] of Russia. 

</TEXT>

