<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Foreign Capital Survives"] </F>
  [Text] According to figures from the St. Petersburg joint 
ventures association, there are about 8,000 joint ventures 
registered in the city (according to the new terminology they 
are called AOZT [private joint-stock companies] in the form of a 
joint venture). No more than 10-12 percent of these engage in 
production. The rest conduct commercial activity or exist purely 
on paper--so that they can be "on hand" in case the tax climate 
in Russia warms up. Under the current conditions foreign 
investors do not see any point in creating any productions of 
any kind in St. Petersburg. Promises from the federal government 
to grant exemptions to enterprises in which foreign capital 
participates have not been kept. But the number of joint 
ventures, including of a production profile, is growing. For 
example, a joint venture has been created for construction of a 
plant for producing mini-electric power plants and a plant for 
producing cigarettes under licenses. They will begin to work if 
the tax burden is lightened. 
  At the same time it is expected that there will be a 
reduction of the activity and possibly the elimination of a 
number of joint ventures of a trade profile engaging in the 
delivery of imported food. The new customs payments introduced 
effective 1 July (announced in the spring) will make food 
deliveries disadvantageous since even the least expensive 
foreign products, taking customs payments into account, will be 
priced too high for the city's rank-and-file residents. 

</TEXT>

